<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-217-045  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 217 045.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Dec 1989 v18 n16 p111(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Metropolitan area network update: the global LAN is gettingcloser. (includes related article on asynchronous transfer modeswitching)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mollenauer, Jim.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The metropolitan area network (MAN), an extension of theshared-access local area network (LAN), which covers a city andits suburbs, is designed to take advantage of the great speedsthat fiber optics make possible.andP;  A company's LANs and wide areanetworks (WAN) have different speed requirements; MANs will fillthat speed gap by 1992.andP;  At first, MAN implementations will beoffered under the regional Bell operating companies' 45M-bpsSwitched Multimegabit Data Service (SMDS).andP;  Later implementationswill run over 155M-bps broadband ISDN.andP;  Various schemes forimplementing MANs are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Metropolitan Area NetworksOutlookFiber optics.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Types of service. (chart)Keeping a standard structure. (chart)Segmentation. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>